    <main id="main">
      <div id="background">
        <header id="title"><b>The Beatles</b></header>
        <div id="img-div">
          <img id="image" alt="The Beatles" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/4/42/Beatles_-_Abbey_Road.jpg" />
          <div id="img-caption">The Beatles - The Greatest Band of All Time</div>
        </div>

        <div id="tribute-info">
          <ul>
            <li><b>Love Me Do</b> – October 5, 1962<br><br>
              The Beatles’ debut single, recorded at Abbey Road Studios. It introduced the world to their signature harmonies and simple yet catchy songwriting.
            </li>
            <li><b>Please Please Me</b> – January 11, 1963<br><br>
              Their first UK No. 1 hit, setting the stage for Beatlemania.
            </li>
            <li><b>She Loves You</b> – August 23, 1963<br><br>
              One of the UK’s best-selling singles, famous for its "Yeah, yeah, yeah" chorus.
            </li>
            <li><b>I Want to Hold Your Hand</b> – November 29, 1963<br><br>
              The song that launched The Beatles in America and started the British Invasion.
            </li>
            <li><b>A Hard Day’s Night</b> – July 10, 1964<br><br>
              Featured in their first movie, with George Harrison’s iconic 12-string guitar sound.
            </li>
            <li><b>Help!</b> – July 19, 1965<br><br>
              John Lennon's introspective cry for help, later seen as a reflection of his stress.
            </li>
            <li><b>Yesterday</b> – September 13, 1965<br><br>
              A McCartney masterpiece, one of the most covered songs ever.
            </li>
            <li><b>Paperback Writer</b> – May 30, 1966<br><br>
              A unique storytelling track with revolutionary vocal harmonies.
            </li>
            <li><b>Strawberry Fields Forever / Penny Lane</b> – February 13, 1967<br><br>
              Two nostalgic childhood-themed tracks that showcased The Beatles’ psychedelic sound.
            </li>
            <li><b>Lucy in the Sky with Diamonds</b> – June 1, 1967<br><br>
              A dreamy, surreal classic from *Sgt. Pepper’s Lonely Hearts Club Band*.
            </li>
            <li><b>All You Need Is Love</b> – July 7, 1967<br><br>
              A global peace anthem, premiered in the first-ever worldwide TV broadcast.
            </li>
            <li><b>Hey Jude</b> – August 26, 1968<br><br>
              A heartfelt McCartney ballad for John Lennon’s son Julian, with an unforgettable singalong.
            </li>
            <li><b>Come Together</b> – October 6, 1969<br><br>
              A bluesy, funky track from *Abbey Road* with mysterious lyrics.
            </li>
            <li><b>Let It Be</b> – March 6, 1970<br><br>
              The band’s farewell hit, inspired by McCartney’s dream of his mother.
            </li>
          </ul>
          <h4>To find out more about The Beatles, check out their 
            <a id="tribute-link" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Beatles" target="_blank">Wikipedia entry.</a>
          </h4>
        </div>
